# Static Blocks
    So you’ve already learned about static variables (those shared kids in the class) and static methods (those overachievers who don’t wait for objects).
    Now, meet the most underrated, low-key heroes of Java — static blocks.

    Let’s say you’re building a Java program for your school’s student app. You want to show a welcome message as soon as the app starts,
    or maybe you want to set a value for a static variable after doing a little logic. You could write this in the main() method…
    but that’s like putting your intro inside the main drama — it just feels messy.

    So how can you run setup code even before the main() method starts running?
    That’s where the static block steps in quietly and does the job. 🛠️✨

Q1. What Exactly Is a Static Block?
    It’s a block of code that Java runs automatically when your class is loaded into memory. And guess what?
    You don’t have to call it. You don’t even need an object. It’s like that one student who shows up early,
    sets up all the chairs, wipes the board, sharpens everyone’s pencils… and disappears before anyone notices.

Standard Definition:
    A static block in Java is a block of code written inside static { }. It runs one time when the class is loaded by the Java Virtual Machine (JVM).
    You don’t call it. It runs on its own.

    Here’s what a static block looks like:
        static {
            // setup code here
        }

    Java sees this block and says,
        “Need to run some setup before anything else? Java uses the static block to do that — no extra steps needed.”

Key Takeaways:
    1. A static block runs once, when the class is loaded
    2. It runs before the main() method
    3. You don’t need to call it
    4. It’s used to initialize static variables or do one-time setup
    5. It cannot access non-static (instance) members
    6. You can have more than one static block — and they run in the order they appear

Common Interview Questions:

    Q1. When is a static block executed?
        When the class is loaded, before the main() method or object creation.

    Q2. Can a class have more than one static block?
        Yes. If there are multiple static blocks, they run in the order they appear in the code.

    Q3. Can you use instance variables inside a static block?
        No. Static blocks can only access static members because no object exists when it runs.

    Q4. Why do we use static blocks?
        To initialize static variables using logic, show startup messages, or do one-time setup when the class starts.

    Q5. Is it necessary to have a static block in a class?
        No. It's optional. Use it only if you need to run setup code before anything else.